{
  "answer": "**The work is *Parāśara Smṛti*, Chapter 7.**\n\nThe relevant verses are Par_7.4–7 (verses 4–6), which assign these age-based names to an unmarried girl and warn of the consequences for her father if she reaches puberty without being married by age twelve:\n\n> An eight-year-old girl is a Gaurī; a nine-year-old is a Rohiṇī.[^1]  \n> A ten-year-old girl is a Kanyā; after that, she is a *rajasvalā* (a menstruating woman). He who does not give his daughter in marriage when she has reached her twelfth year,[^2]  \n> her ancestors themselves drink her menstrual blood month after month.[^3]\n\n[^1]: *Parāśara Smṛti*, [Chapter 7, Par_7.4](/works/unknown-parasara-smrti-2259be/07/translation/#p-dda364).\n\n[^2]: *Parāśara Smṛti*, [Chapter 7, Par_7.5](/works/unknown-parasara-smrti-2259be/07/translation/#p-4665dc).\n\n[^3]: *Parāśara Smṛti*, [Chapter 7, Par_7.6](/works/unknown-parasara-smrti-2259be/07/translation/#p-513c49).",
